# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: change-data-capture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] In databases, **change data capture** (**CDC**) is a set of software design patterns used to determine and track the data that has changed (the "deltas") so that action can be taken using the changed data.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The result is a **delta-driven dataset**.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] CDC is an approach to data integration that is based on the identification, capture and delivery of the changes made to enterprise data sources.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] For instance it can be used for incremental update of data loading.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] CDC occurs often in data warehouse environments since capturing and preserving the state of data across time is one of the core functions of a data warehouse, but CDC can be utilized in any database or data repository system.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] System developers can set up CDC mechanisms in a number of ways and in any one or a combination of system layers from application logic down to physical storage.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] In a simplified CDC context, one computer system has data believed to have changed from a previous point in time, and a second computer system needs to take action based on that changed data.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The former is the source, the latter is the target.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] It is possible that the source and target are the same system physically, but that would not change the design pattern logically.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Multiple CDC solutions can exist in a single system.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Tables whose changes must be captured may have a column that represents the time of **last** change.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Names such as LAST_UPDATE, LAST_MODIFIED, etc. are common.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Any row in any table that has a timestamp in that column that is more recent than the last time data was captured is considered to have changed.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Timestamps on rows are also frequently used for optimistic locking so this column is often available.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Database designers give tables whose changes must be captured a column that contains a version number.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Names such as VERSION_NUMBER, etc. are common.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] One technique is to mark each changed row with a version number.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] A current version is maintained for the table, or possibly a group of tables.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This is stored in a supporting construct such as a reference table.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] When a change capture occurs, all data with the latest version number is considered to have changed.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Once the change capture is complete, the reference table is updated with a new version number.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] (Do not confuse this technique with row-level versioning used for optimistic locking.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] For optimistic locking each row has an independent version number, typically a sequential counter.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This allows a process to atomically update a row and increment its counter only if another process has not incremented the counter.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] But CDC cannot use row-level versions to find all changes unless it knows the original "starting" version of every row.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This technique can either supplement or complement timestamps and versioning.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] It can configure an alternative if, for example, a status column is set up on a table row indicating that the row has changed (e.g., a boolean column that, when set to true, indicates that the row has changed).
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Otherwise, it can act as a complement to the previous methods, indicating that a row, despite having a new version number or a later date, still shouldn't be updated on the target (for example, the data may require human validation).
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This approach combines the three previously discussed methods.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] As noted, it is not uncommon to see multiple CDC solutions at work in a single system, however, the combination of time, version, and status provides a particularly powerful mechanism and programmers should utilize them as a trio where possible.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The three elements are not redundant or superfluous.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] May include a publish/subscribe pattern to communicate the changed data to multiple targets.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] In this approach, triggers log events that happen to the transactional table into another queue table that can later be "played back".
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] For example, imagine an Accounts table, when transactions are taken against this table, triggers would fire that would then store a history of the event or even the deltas into a separate queue table.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The queue table might have schema with the following fields: Id, TableName, RowId, Timestamp, Operation.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The data inserted for our Account sample might be: 1, Accounts, 76, 2008-11-02 00:15, Update.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] More complicated designs might log the actual data that changed.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This queue table could then be "played back" to replicate the data from the source system to a target.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Data capture offers a challenge in that the structure, contents and use of a transaction log is specific to a database management system.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Unlike data access, no standard exists for transaction logs.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Most database management systems do not document the internal format of their transaction logs, although some provide programmatic interfaces to their transaction logs (for example: Oracle, DB2, SQL/MP, SQL/MX and SQL Server 2008).
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] As often occurs in complex domains, the final solution to a CDC problem may have to balance many competing concerns.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Change data capture both increases in complexity and reduces in value if the source system saves metadata changes when the data itself is not modified.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] For example, some Data models track the user who last looked at but did not change the data in the same structure as the data.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] This results in noise in the Change Data Capture.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Actually tracking the changes depends on the data source.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] If the data is being persisted in a modern database then Change Data Capture is a simple matter of permissions.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] If the data is not in a modern database, CDC becomes a programming challenge.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] Sometimes the slowly changing dimension is used as an alternative method.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] CDC and SCD are similar in that both methods can detect changes in a data set.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] The most common forms of SCD are type 1 (overwrite), type 2 (maintain history) or 3 (only previous and current value).
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] SCD 2 can be useful if history is needed in the target system.
[src:change-data-capture/change-data-capture] CDC overwrites in the target system (akin to SCD1), and is ideal when only the changed data needs to arrive at the target, i.e. a *delta-driven dataset*.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:change-data-capture/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] A **database trigger** is procedural code that is automatically executed in response to certain events on a particular table or view in a database.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The trigger is mostly used for maintaining the integrity of the information on the database.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] For example, when a new record (representing a new worker) is added to the employees table, new records should also be created in the tables of the taxes, vacations and salaries.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Triggers can also be used to log historical data, for example to keep track of employees' previous salaries.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Below follows a series of descriptions of how some common DBMS support triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] In addition to triggers that fire (and execute PL/SQL code) when data is modified, Oracle 10g supports triggers that fire when schema-level objects (that is, tables) are modified and when user logon or logoff events occur.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Column-level trigger: This gets executed before or after the *specified column* changes.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] For each row type: This trigger gets executed once for each row of the result set affected by an insert/update/delete.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] For each statement type: This trigger gets executed only once for the entire result set, but also fires each time the statement is executed.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] From Oracle 8i, database events - logons, logoffs, startups - can fire Oracle triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] MS SQL Server supports trigger for DML and DDL statement plus special trigger "logon".
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The scope of DDL triggers can be a database (CREATE TRIGGER name ON DATABASE ...) or the entire SQL Server instance (CREATE TRIGGER name ON ALL SERVER).
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] When you use the entire instance, you can capture all events executed on commands that have server-level scope as well as any commands that have database-level scope in the SQL instance.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] A list of all available firing events in Microsoft SQL Server for DDL triggers is available on Microsoft Docs.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Performing conditional actions in DML triggers (or testing data following modification) is done through accessing the pseudo tables (temporary ones) Inserted and Deleted tables.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] DML trigger are always "FOR EACH STATEMENT" but can be code at row event ("FOR EACH ROW") using a cursor on the inserted/deleted pseudo tables.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Introduced support for triggers in 1997.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Database-level triggers can help enforce multi-table constraints, or emulate materialized views.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Limited support for triggers in the MySQL/MariaDB DBMS was added in the 5.0 version of MySQL, launched in 2005.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] As of version 8.0, they allow for DDL (Data Definition Language) triggers and for DML (Data Manipulation Language) triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] They also allow either type of DDL trigger (AFTER or BEFORE) to be used to define triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] They are created by using the clause *CREATE TRIGGER* and deleted by using the clause *DROP TRIGGER*.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The statement called upon an event happens is defined after the clause *FOR EACH ROW*, followed by a keyword (*SET* or *BEGIN*), which indicates whether what follows is an expression or a statement respectively.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] IBM DB2 for distributed systems known as DB2 for LUW (LUW means **L**inux, **U**nix, **W**indows) supports three trigger types: Before trigger, After trigger and Instead of trigger.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Both statement level and row level triggers are supported.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] If there are more triggers for same operation on table then firing order is determined by trigger creation data.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Since version 9.7 IBM DB2 supports autonomous transactions.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Before trigger is for checking data and deciding if operation should be permitted.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] If exception is thrown from before trigger then operation is aborted and no data are changed.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] In DB2 before triggers are read only — you can't modify data in before triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] After triggers are designed for post processing after requested change was performed.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] After triggers can write data into tables and unlike some other databases you can write into any table including table on which trigger operates.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Instead of triggers are for making views writeable.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Triggers are usually programmed in SQL PL language.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] SQLite only supports row-level triggers, not statement-level triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Updateable views, which are not supported in SQLite, can be emulated with INSTEAD OF triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] An example of implementation of triggers in non-relational database can be Sedna, that provides support for triggers based on XQuery.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Triggers in Sedna were designed to be analogous to SQL:2003 triggers, but natively base on XML query and update languages (XPath, XQuery and XML update language).
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] A trigger in Sedna is set on any nodes of an XML document stored in database.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] When these nodes are updated, the trigger automatically executes XQuery queries and updates specified in its body.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] To understand how trigger behavior works, you need to be aware of the two main types of triggers; these are Row and Statement level triggers.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The distinction between the two is how many times the code within the trigger is executed, and at what time.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Suppose you have a trigger that is made to be called on an UPDATE to a certain table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Row level triggers would execute once for each row that is affected by the UPDATE.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] If no rows are affected by the UPDATE command, the trigger **will not** execute any code within the trigger.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Statement level triggers will be called once **regardless** of how many rows are affected by the UPDATE.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Even if the UPDATE command didn't affect any rows, the code within the trigger will still be executed once.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Using the BEFORE and AFTER options determine when the trigger is called.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Suppose you have a trigger that is called on an INSERT to a certain table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] If your trigger is using the BEFORE option, the code within the trigger will be executed before the INSERT into the table occurs.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] A common use of the BEFORE trigger is to verify the input values of the INSERT, or modify the values accordingly.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Now let's say we have a trigger that uses AFTER instead.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The code within the trigger is executed after the INSERT happens to the table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] An example use of this trigger is creating an audit history of who has made inserts into the database, keeping track of the changes made.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] When using these options you need to keep a few things in mind.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The BEFORE option does **not allow** you to modify tables, that is why input validation is a practical use.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Using AFTER triggers allows you to modify tables such as inserting into an audit history table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] When creating a trigger to determine if it is statement or row level simply include the FOR EACH ROW clause for a row level, or omit the clause for a statement level.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Be cautious of using additional INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE commands within your trigger, because trigger recursion is possible, causing unwanted behavior.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] In the examples below each trigger is modifying a different table, by looking at what is being modified you can see some common applications of when different trigger types are used.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The following is an Oracle syntax example of a row level trigger that is called AFTER an update FOR EACH ROW affected.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] This trigger is called on an update to a phone book database.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] When the trigger is called it adds an entry into a separate table named phone_book_audit.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Also take note of triggers being able to take advantage of schema objects like sequences, in this example audit_id_sequence.nexVal is used to generate unique primary keys in the phone_book_audit table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Now calling an UPDATE on the phone_book table for people with the last name 'Jones'.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Notice that the phone_number_audit table is now populated with two entries.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] This is due to the database having two entries with the last name of 'Jones'.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Since the update modified two separate row values, the created trigger was called twice; once after each modification.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] An Oracle syntax statement trigger that is called after an UPDATE to the phone_book table.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Now doing exactly the same update as the above example, however this time with a statement level trigger.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The result shows that the trigger was only called once, even though the update did change two rows.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] This example demonstrates a BEFORE EACH ROW trigger that modifies the INSERT using a WHEN conditional.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] If the last name is larger than 10 letters, using the SUBSTR function we change the last_name column value to an abbreviation.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Now performing an INSERT of someone with a large name.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] The trigger worked as per the result above, modifying the value of the INSERT **before** it was executed.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Using a BEFORE statement trigger is particularly useful when enforcing database restrictions.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] This example demonstrate how to enforce a restriction upon someone named "SOMEUSER" on the table phone_book.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Custom errors such as this one has a restriction on what the num variable can be defined as.
[src:change-data-capture/database-trigger] Because of the numerous other pre-defined errors this variable must be in the range of −20000 to −20999.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Eventually-consistent services are often classified as providing BASE semantics (basically-available, soft-state, eventual consistency), in contrast to traditional ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability).
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Eventual consistency faces criticism for adding complexity to distributed software applications.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] This complexity arises because eventual consistency provides only a liveness guarantee (ensuring reads eventually return the same value) without safety guarantees—allowing any intermediate value before convergence.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Application developers find this challenging because it differs from single-threaded programming, where variables reliably return their assigned values immediately.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] With weak consistency guarantees, developers must carefully consider these limitations, as incorrect assumptions about consistency levels can lead to subtle bugs that only surface during network failures or high concurrency.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] In order to ensure replica convergence, a system must reconcile differences between multiple copies of distributed data.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] The most appropriate approach to reconciliation depends on the application.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] A widespread approach is "last writer wins".
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Another is to invoke a user-specified conflict handler.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Timestamps and vector clocks are often used to detect concurrency between updates.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Some people use "first writer wins" in situations where "last writer wins" is unacceptable.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] Whereas eventual consistency is only a liveness guarantee (updates will be observed eventually), **strong eventual consistency** (SEC) adds the safety guarantee that any two nodes that have received the same (unordered) set of updates will be in the same state.
[src:change-data-capture/eventual-consistency] A common approach to ensure SEC is conflict-free replicated data types.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Replication in space or in time is often linked to scheduling algorithms.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Access to a replicated entity is typically uniform with access to a single non-replicated entity.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The replication itself should be transparent to an external user.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In a failure scenario, a failover of replicas should be hidden as much as possible with respect to quality of service.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] When one leader replica is designated via leader election to process all the requests, the system is using a primary-backup or primary-replica scheme, which is predominant in high-availability clusters.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In comparison, if any replica can process a request and distribute a new state, the system is using a multi-primary or multi-master scheme.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In the latter case, some form of distributed concurrency control must be used, such as a distributed lock manager.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Load balancing differs from task replication, since it distributes a load of different computations across machines, and allows a single computation to be dropped in case of failure.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Load balancing, however, sometimes uses data replication (especially multi-master replication) internally, to distribute its data among machines.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Backup differs from replication in that the saved copy of data remains unchanged for a long period of time.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Replicas, on the other hand, undergo frequent updates and quickly lose any historical state.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Replication is one of the oldest and most important topics in the overall area of distributed systems.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Data replication and computation replication both require processes to handle incoming events.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Processes for data replication are passive and operate only to maintain the stored data, reply to read requests and apply updates.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Computation replication is usually performed to provide fault-tolerance, and take over an operation if one component fails.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In both cases, the underlying needs are to ensure that the replicas see the same events in equivalent orders, so that they stay in consistent states and any replica can respond to queries.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Database replication involves maintaining copies of the same data on multiple machines, typically implemented through three main approaches: single-leader, multi-leader, and leaderless replication.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In single-leader (also called primary/replica) replication, one database instance is designated as the leader (primary), which handles all write operations.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The leader logs these updates, which then propagate to replica nodes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Each replica acknowledges receipt of updates, enabling subsequent write operations.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Replicas primarily serve read requests, though they may serve stale data due to replication lag – the delay in propagating changes from the leader.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In multi-master replication (also called multi-leader), updates can be submitted to any database node, which then propagate to other servers.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This approach is particularly beneficial in multi-data center deployments, where it enables local write processing while masking inter-data center network latency.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] However, it introduces substantially increased costs and complexity which may make it impractical in some situations.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The most common challenge that exists in multi-master replication is transactional conflict prevention or resolution when concurrent modifications occur on different leader nodes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Most synchronous (or eager) replication solutions perform conflict prevention, while asynchronous (or lazy) solutions have to perform conflict resolution.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For instance, if the same record is changed on two nodes simultaneously, an eager replication system would detect the conflict before confirming the commit and abort one of the transactions.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A lazy replication system would allow both transactions to commit and run a conflict resolution during re-synchronization.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Conflict resolution methods can include techniques like last-write-wins, application-specific logic, or merging concurrent updates.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] However, replication transparency can not always be achieved.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] When data is replicated in a database, they will be constrained by CAP theorem or PACELC theorem.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In the NoSQL movement, data consistency is usually sacrificed in exchange for other more desired properties, such as availability (A), partition tolerance (P), etc.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Various data consistency models have also been developed to serve as Service Level Agreement (SLA) between service providers and the users.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Active (real-time) storage replication is usually implemented by distributing updates of a block device to several physical hard disks.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This way, any file system supported by the operating system can be replicated without modification, as the file system code works on a level above the block device driver layer.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] It is implemented either in hardware (in a disk array controller) or in software (in a device driver).
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The most basic method is disk mirroring, which is typical for locally connected disks.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The storage industry narrows the definitions, so *mirroring* is a local (short-distance) operation.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A replication is extendable across a computer network, so that the disks can be located in physically distant locations, and the primary/replica database replication model is usually applied.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The purpose of replication is to prevent damage from failures or disasters that may occur in one location – or in case such events do occur, to improve the ability to recover data.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For replication, latency is the key factor because it determines either how far apart the sites can be or the type of replication that can be employed.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The main characteristic of such cross-site replication is how write operations are handled, through either asynchronous or synchronous replication; synchronous replication needs to wait for the destination server's response in any write operation whereas asynchronous replication does not.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Synchronous replication guarantees "zero data loss" by the means of atomic write operations, where the write operation is not considered complete until acknowledged by both the local and remote storage.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Most applications wait for a write transaction to complete before proceeding with further work, hence overall performance decreases considerably.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Inherently, performance drops proportionally to distance, as minimum latency is dictated by the speed of light.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For 10 km distance, the fastest possible roundtrip takes 67 μs, whereas an entire local cached write completes in about 10–20 μs.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In asynchronous replication, the write operation is considered complete as soon as local storage acknowledges it.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Remote storage is updated with a small lag.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Performance is greatly increased, but in case of a local storage failure, the remote storage is not guaranteed to have the current copy of data (the most recent data may be lost).
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Semi-synchronous replication typically considers a write operation complete when acknowledged by local storage and received or logged by the remote server.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The actual remote write is performed asynchronously, resulting in better performance but remote storage will lag behind the local storage, so that there is no guarantee of durability (i.e., seamless transparency) in the case of local storage failure.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Point-in-time replication produces periodic snapshots which are replicated instead of primary storage.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This is intended to replicate only the changed data instead of the entire volume.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] As less information is replicated using this method, replication can occur over less-expensive bandwidth links such as iSCSI or T1 instead of fiberoptic lines.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Many distributed filesystems use replication to ensure fault tolerance and avoid a single point of failure.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Many commercial synchronous replication systems do not freeze when the remote replica fails or loses connection – behaviour which guarantees zero data loss – but proceed to operate locally, losing the desired zero recovery point objective.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Techniques of wide-area network (WAN) optimization can be applied to address the limits imposed by latency.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] File-based replication conducts data replication at the logical level (i.e., individual data files) rather than at the storage block level.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] There are many different ways of performing this, which almost exclusively rely on software.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A kernel driver (specifically a filter driver) can be used to intercept calls to the filesystem functions, capturing any activity as it occurs.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This uses the same type of technology that real-time active virus checkers employ.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] At this level, logical file operations are captured like file open, write, delete, etc.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The kernel driver transmits these commands to another process, generally over a network to a different machine, which will mimic the operations of the source machine.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Like block-level storage replication, the file-level replication allows both synchronous and asynchronous modes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In synchronous mode, write operations on the source machine are held and not allowed to occur until the destination machine has acknowledged the successful replication.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Synchronous mode is less common with file replication products although a few solutions exist.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] File-level replication solutions allow for informed decisions about replication based on the location and type of the file.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For example, temporary files or parts of a filesystem that hold no business value could be excluded.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The data transmitted can also be more granular; if an application writes 100 bytes, only the 100 bytes are transmitted instead of a complete disk block (generally 4,096 bytes).
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This substantially reduces the amount of data sent from the source machine and the storage burden on the destination machine.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Drawbacks of this software-only solution include the requirement for implementation and maintenance on the operating system level, and an increased burden on the machine's processing power.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Similarly to database transaction logs, many file systems have the ability to journal their activity.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The journal can be sent to another machine, either periodically or in real time by streaming.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] On the replica side, the journal can be used to play back file system modifications.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is Microsoft's System Center Data Protection Manager (DPM), released in 2005, which performs periodic updates but does not offer real-time replication.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This is the process of comparing the source and destination file systems and ensuring that the destination matches the source.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The key benefit is that such solutions are generally free or inexpensive.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The downside is that the process of synchronizing them is quite system-intensive, and consequently this process generally runs infrequently.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] One of the notable implementations is rsync.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In a paging operating system, pages in a paging file are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In IBM's VSAM, index data are sometimes replicated within a track to reduce rotational latency.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Another example of using replication appears in distributed shared memory systems, where many nodes of the system share the same page of memory.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This usually means that each node has a separate copy (replica) of a specific page.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Many classical approaches to replication are based on a primary-backup model where one device or process has unilateral control over one or more other processes or devices.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For example, the primary might perform some computation, streaming a log of updates to a backup (standby) process, which can then take over if the primary fails.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This approach is common for replicating databases, despite the risk that if a portion of the log is lost during a failure, the backup might not be in a state identical to the primary, and transactions could then be lost.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A weakness of primary-backup schemes is that only one is actually performing operations.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Fault-tolerance is gained, but the identical backup system doubles the costs.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] 1985, the distributed systems research community began to explore alternative methods of replicating data.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] An outgrowth of this work was the emergence of schemes in which a group of replicas could cooperate, with each process acting as a backup while also handling a share of the workload.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Computer scientist Jim Gray analyzed multi-primary replication schemes under the transactional model and published a widely cited paper skeptical of the approach "The Dangers of Replication and a Solution".
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] He argued that unless the data splits in some natural way so that the database can be treated as *n* disjoint sub-databases, concurrency control conflicts will result in seriously degraded performance and the group of replicas will probably slow as a function of *n*.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Gray suggested that the most common approaches are likely to result in degradation that scales as *O(n³)*.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] His solution, which is to partition the data, is only viable in situations where data actually has a natural partitioning key.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] In the 1985–1987, the virtual synchrony model was proposed and emerged as a widely adopted standard (it was used in the Isis Toolkit, Horus, Transis, Ensemble, Totem, Spread, C-Ensemble, Phoenix and Quicksilver systems, and is the basis for the CORBA fault-tolerant computing standard).
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Virtual synchrony permits a multi-primary approach in which a group of processes cooperates to parallelize some aspects of request processing.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] The scheme can only be used for some forms of in-memory data, but can provide linear speedups in the size of the group.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A number of modern products support similar schemes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] For example, the Spread Toolkit supports this same virtual synchrony model and can be used to implement a multi-primary replication scheme; it would also be possible to use C-Ensemble or Quicksilver in this manner.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] WANdisco permits active replication where every node on a network is an exact copy or replica and hence every node on the network is active at one time; this scheme is optimized for use in a wide area network (WAN).
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Modern multi-primary replication protocols optimize for the common failure-free operation.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] Chain replication is a popular family of such protocols.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] State-of-the-art protocol variants of chain replication offer high throughput and strong consistency by arranging replicas in a chain for writes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This approach enables local reads on all replica nodes but has high latency for writes that must traverse multiple nodes sequentially.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] A more recent multi-primary protocol, Hermes, combines cache-coherent-inspired invalidations and logical timestamps to achieve strong consistency with local reads and high-performance writes from all replicas.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] During fault-free operation, its broadcast-based writes are non-conflicting and commit after just one multicast round-trip to replica nodes.
[src:change-data-capture/replication-computing] This design results in high throughput and low latency for both reads and writes.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] In computer science, **write-ahead logging** (**WAL**) is a family of techniques for providing atomicity and durability (two of the ACID properties) in database systems.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] A write ahead log is an append-only auxiliary disk-resident structure used for crash and transaction recovery.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] The changes are first recorded in the log, which must be written to stable storage, before the changes are written to the database.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] In a system using WAL, all modifications are written to a log before they are applied.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] Usually both redo and undo information is stored in the log.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] The purpose of this can be illustrated by an example.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] Imagine a program that is in the middle of performing some operation when the machine it is running on loses power.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] Upon restart, that program might need to know whether the operation it was performing succeeded, succeeded partially, or failed.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] If a write-ahead log is used, the program can check this log and compare what it was supposed to be doing when it unexpectedly lost power to what was actually done.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] On the basis of this comparison, the program could decide to undo what it had started, complete what it had started, or keep things as they are.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] After a certain number of operations, the program should perform a checkpoint, writing all the changes specified in the WAL to the database and clearing the log.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] WAL allows updates of a database to be done in-place.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] Another way to implement atomic updates is with shadow paging, which is not in-place.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] The main advantage of doing updates in-place is that it reduces the need to modify indexes and block lists.
[src:change-data-capture/write-ahead-logging] Modern file systems typically use a variant of WAL for at least file system metadata; this is called journaling.
